The paper deals with the computational complexity of solving random $k$-SAT instances, which is a fundamental problem in theoretical computer science. The Super-Strong ETH is a hypothesis related to the worst-case complexity of $k$-SAT, which falls under the category of computational complexity (cs.CC). The paper also discusses various algorithmic paradigms such as backtracking, local search, and the polynomial method, which are commonly used in the design and analysis of algorithms, and hence the paper could also be classified under cs.DS (data structures and algorithms). The use of randomized algorithms and the analysis of their running time make the paper relevant to the subfield of artificial intelligence (cs.AI). The paper also involves the study of random graphs and their properties, which is a topic in discrete mathematics (cs.DM). Finally, the paper could be classified under cs.CG (computational geometry) as it involves the analysis of the geometry of high-dimensional spaces, which is relevant to the study of random $k$-SAT instances.
